In order to assess and analyze the difference or variance between p1 predictions and p2 or p3 predicitions, I had to create three columns that measure the variances between p1 & p2 prediction confidence percentages, p1 & p3 prediction confidence percentages, and lastly p2 & p3 prediction confidence percentages; I named those columns p1_p2_var, p1_p3_var and p2_p3_var.

My goal here was to hopefully explore any anomalies that may lay hidden within the data, specifically prediction confidence percentages for the algorithm's 'educated guesses or predictions'. First, I'll display the visualizations, then I'll explain the analysis.

In [7]:
# creating my variance columns
img_prd_df_cln['p1_p2_var'] = (img_prd_df_cln['p1_conf'] - img_prd_df_cln['p2_conf'])
img_prd_df_cln['p2_p3_var'] = (img_prd_df_cln['p2_conf'] - img_prd_df_cln['p3_conf'])
img_prd_df_cln['p1_p3_var'] = (img_prd_df_cln['p1_conf'] - img_prd_df_cln['p3_conf'])

Taking a look at the distributions between prediction confidence percentages, I noticed something a bit odd. It seems as though the range of variance, in terms of distribution of variances or differences in prediction percentages, are far less for p2_conf and p3_conf variables, ranging from 0.0 to 0.4. This seems to make sense however, as p2_conf and p3_conf are weaker prediction percentages, compared to p1_conf values.

I chose to run the .describe() method on the twt_df_cpy dataframe to get an idea of the averages, mins and maxes of the of the quantitative data. Here, we can see our favorites or 'Likes' and retweets are our quantitative variables within the data set. Notice the minimum value count for both favorites and retweets is zero. I'm not quite sure if that data is valid or 'highly unlikely' given my unfamiliarity with Twitter. One thing I do notice, however is that the favorites or 'Likes' count is almost twice as much as the retweets count. Let's take a look a some visualizations.

In [15]:
twt_sts_cln_df[['favorites', 'retweets']].plot.line(grid=True, linewidth=0.9, subplots=True, figsize=(17,7))

# adding my labels
plt.title('Twitter API Favorites(Likes) vs. Retweets')
plt.xlabel('Tweet')
plt.ylabel('Retweet Count')
plt.grid(axis='y', alpha=0.75)

What we have here are two distribution range plots for exploratory variables favorites or 'Likes' and retweets. Using a line plot, I've been able to convey the volume of spikes, or jumps/peaks in the data, in either 'Likes' or 'Retweets'. What's interesting here is that there seems to be a spike in both variables around the same if not the same tweet. Data that reveals a pattern such as this should be explored further. Let's take a closer look.

In [16]:

plt.ylabel('Number of Retweets')
Out[16]:

Ahh, here's something interesting, and now that I think of it, should have asssumed as well. Using the scatter plot method, I've been able to convey that the relationship between 'Favorites(Likes)' and 'Retweets' is linear. This means that there is definitely a positive association between to two epxloratory variables, and in exlploratory analysis, and predictive modeling, either variable could be used as a predictor variable to forcast or predict the other. To further solidify my analysis, this inference is and should be confirmed by the line plot above, that conveys spikes within the distributions on the same tweet count.

The first, 'Descriptive Statistics For Each Grouping of Dog Stage', uses a line plot to view the distribution of descriptive statistic values for each grouping of dog stages. The second plot, 'Combined Twitter Dataset Descriptive Statistics' is also grouped by dog stage groupings, but focuses more on displaying the descriptive stats using the boxplot method.

Conclusions¶

We've been able to take a brief synopsis of my analysis, and wrangling efforts and condense it into a short little report. I'm not one for Twitter much, although I do have a profile, and I find it astounding that people have the time to manage their social media profiles as much as they do; especially Twitter, which for me, is literally "tell the world every breathing moment of your life, and do it under a 140 characters." It just seems like too much to me. That being said, it's quite clear that from my analysis hundreds of thousands of people think differently.

@WeRateDogs has garnered quite the popularity on the social media platform. Analyzing their data helped me understand a few things about the user of the platform. Now this observation is obviously biased, because I've only assesed one user's data for a certain period of time, but it seems as though @WeRateDogs preferred method of 'posting' seems to be their iPhone. 94% of their tweets are delivered through the device. We also recognized the linear relationship between 'favorites' or 'likes' and 'retweets'.

I had few limitations when it came to wrangling this tweet data. For one, querying an API was new exposure for me so that learning curve took a little while to get past. Handling JSON data formatting as well, with understanding when to use load(s)() vs. dump(s)() took a few attempts at re-reading 'Read a File Line-by-Line in Python' from 'Stackabuse.com'. I surprisingly found structural or tidyness issues to be easier to fix than data quality issues. But, I guess that is to be expected considering I was using RegEx's .str.extract() and .str.replace() methods to do a bit of cleaning. My inexperience with Twitter's platform leaves a lot wanting when it comes to what data to extract or query the API for. I hope with more exposure and time, I can come back to this project and really fix it up nice.
